by The Fallen City of Rapture » Fri Sep 03, 2021 7:39 pm

Take a drink when someone says they are guilty of a cliché on this thread.

Now, I know you guys are not my Manchurian candidates, neither Cocker Spaniels, but would you kindly listen to my incoherent ramblings one more time?

The “Obviously Bad Guys” versus the “Obviously Good Guys” formula in wars that almost everybody adheres to. Okay, I understand it’s easy for people to write a war that explains how this faction (the Good Guys who do good stuff) and the other faction (the Bad Guys who do bad stuff) fought each other in battles on an epic scale. But don’t think I’m gonna root for the obviously good guys if they are shallow and generic and not…human. (Not the noun, I mean the adjective meaning for the word human. This goes for the obviously bad guys.) In most of the factbooks I’ve read, and aside from the bad guys doing all the bad stuff, it’s all played out like a blockbuster movie with a foreordained ending, with explosions and obvious heroes defeating the super evil people and everything is nice and dandy.

Now I would like to use Call of Duty: World at War as an example of what I am saying when it comes to writing and portraying any conflict, including the people and factions in them. In the fourth mission Vendetta in the game’s Soviet campaign, we get to witness how brutal and ruthless the soldiers of Nazi Germany were to the soldiers and people in Stalingrad; they were searching for survivors who are dying among the dead and killing them in cold blood. So this sets up the Germans as our enemies obviously on this side of the game’s Eastern Front campaign. And damn, Dimitri Petrenko (controlled by the player) survived because he played dead and only moves around when the death squads move on. Dimitri Petrenko and Viktor Reznov, who also feigned death among his comrades and survives, were focused on surviving in order to kill one man. They knew they stood no chance fighting against a hundred enemy soldiers who are cold, merciless, and hellbent on destroying them. But later in the Soviet campaign, the roles (kind of) reversed. While advancing into Nazi Germany through Seelow Heights, Viktor Reznov (and all the soldiers of the Red Army) is now cruel, ruthless and brutal as the Germans were during the war. The Germans are now desperate and frantically trying to fight off the swathes of Red Army soldiers to no avail, just holding back their inevitable demise. Reznov is hellbent on not just defeating the Third Reich, but destroying it absolutely. But Reznov stands in contrast to Private Chernov, who is the more merciful and humane characters in the game. But not all of Chernov’s comrades share his merciful and peaceful sentiment because it is overshadowed by the rage and vengefulness of the Red Army and the whole Soviet Union; and because the Nazis razed their homeland, the Soviets are very willing to do the exact same thing to the Germans. Even though we understand the Soviets and their motivation to destroy Hitler’s Third Reich, and we remember the atrocities and obscenities inflicted upon them by the Nazis during the war, we do not excuse the Red Army’s series of violent atrocities and obscenities they’ve inflicted upon the German populace.

But you guys don’t have to take to heart on what I said, but what I am really trying to say is: Just try writing a war that makes me feel emotional; show to me and make me hate the obscenities and evils from that war, like the wars in the past and the ones today; don’t elevate one side on a higher pedestal and lower the other side in insignificance; try to humanize even some of the belligerents if possible.

Tbh those kinds of things would only interest me if there's deeper lore than just a list of things.
